      "question": "If the HCF of $126$ and $45$ is expressed in the form $126x + 45y = 9$, find one possible integer pair $(x, y)$ such that $x$ and $y$ are integers.",
      "answer": "$x = 1, y = -3$ (or other valid integer solutions)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use Euclid's division algorithm to find the HCF of $126$ and $45$.",
          "Express the HCF $9$ as a linear combination of $126$ and $45$ by backtracking the steps of the division algorithm."
        ],
        "derivation": "$126 = 45 \\times 2 + 36 \\\\ 45 = 36 \\times 1 + 9 \\\\ 9 = 45 - 36 \\times 1 \\\\ 9 = 45 - (126 - 45 \\times 2) \\\\ 9 = 45 - 126 + 45 \\times 2 \\\\ 9 = 126(-1) + 45(3) \\\\ \\text{Alternatively, using } 126(1) + 45(-3) = 9 \\\\ \\Rightarrow x = 1, y = -3$"
      },
